{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0,0.06,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10721"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7166"},{"type":"tags","id":"8508"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial plexus is a network\u00a0of nerves that innervates the skin and muscles of the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vertebral levels is NOT a part of the brachial plexus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C4","C5","C6","C7","T1"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the lower four cervical nerves and the first thoracic nerve, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003ET1\u003C/strong\u003E. These nerves combine to form the roots of the brachial plexus, which then give rise to the trunks, divisions, cords, and branches that innervate the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the brachial plexus. It primarily contributes to the cervical plexus, which innervates the neck and diaphragm. In some individuals, there may be a contribution from C4 to the brachial plexus, but it is not considered a standard component.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomy of the brachial plexus is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions that affect the upper limb, such as nerve injuries or compressive neuropathies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachial plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the lower four cervical nerves (C5-C8) and the first thoracic nerve (T1).","C4 is not part of the brachial plexus, as it primarily contributes to the cervical plexus."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64215"